seem to be very understanding on this. it's not unheard of a non licensed money exchanger on china borders to change counterfeits to travelers. if you're not experienced in checking notes, you're highly advised to go to banks. when you pay with a ¥50 or ¥100 banknote in a shop or taxi, it's socially accepted that you remember the last few digits of your currency number as you pass it. it's possible that they say that your banknote is fake, just make sure you get back what you gave them. changing money[edit] although still restricted, the yuan is readily convertible 